// MARK: - Aries
"constellation.aries.name" = "Aries";
"constellation.aries.description" = "Your star blazes like a flame,\ncutting through the dark sea first,\nawakening the dawn.";
"constellation.aries.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.aries.story.1.content" = "Long ago, when gods still walked the earth.\n\nAtamas, king of Boeotia, had two children — Phrixus and Helle. His new queen Ino despised them, secretly roasting all the kingdom's seeds. When famine came, she forged an oracle demanding the children be sacrificed.\n\nIn that moment, a sacred ram with golden fleece descended from the sky. Sent by Hermes. The ram carried the children on its back and flew through the storm into the heavens.\n\nThe stars made way, and even the wind held its breath.";
"constellation.aries.story.2.title" = "The Journey";
"constellation.aries.story.2.content" = "As the ram raced through the sky, Helle lost her grip and fell.\n\nThe sea below — still called the Hellespont today. Holding Helle's name forever.\n\nPhrixus held on alone, and the ram ran to the end. When they reached Colchis, Phrixus was alive. The ram was offered to the gods, and its golden fleece was hung in a sacred grove.\n\nThat golden fleece would one day be sought by Jason and the Argonauts — but that is another story.\n\nThe ram died, but Zeus placed him in the sky. To remember courage and sacrifice.";
"constellation.aries.story.3.title" = "Hamal — The Ram's Head";
"constellation.aries.story.3.content" = "At the heart of Aries is Hamal.\n\nMeaning 'head of the ram' in Arabic, this star shines about 66 light-years from Earth. It is about 14 times brighter than our sun, a red giant with a warm glow.\n\nThousands of years ago, the vernal equinox — the start of spring — was near this star. Farmers planted seeds when Hamal rose on the horizon, and sailors charted their course.\n\nPrecession has since moved the equinox, but ancient star charts still list Aries first.\n\nThe star of beginnings. Holding the memory of spring.";
"constellation.aries.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.aries.story.4.content" = "You, born between March 21 and April 19.\n\nWhere the golden ram ascended, your star was written.\n\nAries is a star that does not fear beginnings. It ran through the storm, moving forward without knowing the end. That courage quietly shines somewhere in your sky.\n\nTonight, Hamal looks down at you from somewhere in the heavens.\n\nAcross 66 light-years, still today.";
"constellation.aries.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.aries.relation.1.name" = "Taurus";
"constellation.aries.relation.1.desc" = "Lights the spring sky side by side";
"constellation.aries.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.aries.relation.2.name" = "Orion";
"constellation.aries.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through Jason's quest for the golden fleece";
"constellation.aries.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.aries.relation.3.name" = "Gemini";
"constellation.aries.relation.3.desc" = "Shines together in the spring sky";
"constellation.aries.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.aries.relation.4.name" = "Libra";
"constellation.aries.relation.4.desc" = "Balances from the opposite side of the sky";

// MARK: - Taurus
"constellation.taurus.name" = "Taurus";
"constellation.taurus.description" = "Like the deep and quiet earth,\nyour star keeps watch over someone's night\nwith an unwavering light.";
"constellation.taurus.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.taurus.story.1.content" = "Zeus often changed his form. Sometimes an eagle, sometimes a swan.\n\nBut when he saw Europa, princess of Phoenicia, he became a dazzlingly white bull. Europa, picking flowers by the sea, approached the beautiful bull and climbed onto its back.\n\nIn that moment, the bull began to run. Across the sea, through the waves, all the way to the island of Crete.\n\nEuropa was frightened but did not let go. The wind tossed her hair, and the sea shimmered beneath her feet.\n\nZeus placed that bull in the sky to be remembered forever.";
"constellation.taurus.story.2.title" = "The Pleiades — Seven Sisters";
"constellation.taurus.story.2.content" = "Within Taurus lies a small cluster of stars.\n\nThe Pleiades — the seven daughters of Atlas and Pleione. When the hunter Orion pursued them, Zeus transformed them into doves and carried them into the sky.\n\nSix of the seven sisters shine brightly, but one cannot be seen. Some say it is Electra, who vanished when Troy fell. Others say it is Merope, hiding in shame for having loved a mortal.\n\nOn a clear night, look near the shoulder of Taurus and you can meet those sisters. Gathered quietly, warmly together.";
"constellation.taurus.story.3.title" = "Aldebaran — The Bull's Eye";
"constellation.taurus.story.3.content" = "The heart of Taurus, Aldebaran.\n\nMeaning 'the follower' in Arabic — named for following the Pleiades across the sky.\n\nAbout 65 light-years away, a red giant 44 times the size of our sun. Glowing red like the eye of a bull, this star has guided sailors since ancient times.\n\nIn the winter sky before spring arrives, if you see a red star sparkling beside Orion, that is Aldebaran.\n\nEven across 65 light-years, that red gaze is clear.";
"constellation.taurus.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.taurus.story.4.content" = "You, born between April 20 and May 20.\n\nTaurus is a star that is slow but never stops. It was no coincidence that Zeus chose the form of a bull.\n\nTo not be shaken. To walk at your own pace. The steadiness within holds your star.\n\nIf Aldebaran glows red tonight, it is a signal sent to you from 65 light-years away.";
"constellation.taurus.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.taurus.relation.1.name" = "Aries";
"constellation.taurus.relation.1.desc" = "Shines side by side in the spring sky";
"constellation.taurus.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.taurus.relation.2.name" = "Orion";
"constellation.taurus.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through Orion's pursuit of the Pleiades";
"constellation.taurus.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.taurus.relation.3.name" = "Gemini";
"constellation.taurus.relation.3.desc" = "Adorns the winter night sky together";
"constellation.taurus.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.taurus.relation.4.name" = "Scorpius";
"constellation.taurus.relation.4.desc" = "Faces each other from opposite sides of the sky";

// MARK: - Gemini
"constellation.gemini.name" = "Gemini";
"constellation.gemini.description" = "Two lights wrap around each other,\nyour star whispers stories\nsomewhere in the world.";
"constellation.gemini.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.gemini.story.1.content" = "If there is one constellation in the sky most full of warmth, it is Gemini.\n\nCastor and Pollux — born of the same mother, Leda, but different fathers. Castor was the son of a mortal, Pollux the son of Zeus.\n\nSo Castor was fated to die, while Pollux could live forever.\n\nWhen Castor fell in battle, Pollux pleaded with Zeus. To share his immortality. To be with his brother.\n\nZeus received that wish and placed them both side by side in the sky.";
"constellation.gemini.story.2.title" = "Heroes of the Argo";
"constellation.gemini.story.2.content" = "Castor and Pollux sailed with Jason and the Argonauts.\n\nCastor was gifted with horses, and Pollux was a master of boxing. The two brothers always stayed together, protecting each other.\n\nWhen a fierce storm struck during the voyage, sailors saw flames of light shining above the brothers' heads. Legend says that light calmed the storm.\n\nEven today, when two lights appear on a ship, they say 'Castor and Pollux are with us.' A sign of safety.";
"constellation.gemini.story.3.title" = "The Secret of Two Stars";
"constellation.gemini.story.3.content" = "Castor and Pollux shine side by side in the sky too.\n\nCastor is actually a complex system of six stars orbiting each other, about 51 light-years from Earth. Pollux is closer at 28 light-years and is the brightest star in Gemini.\n\nThe two stars are only about 2 degrees apart in the night sky. Like brothers always side by side.\n\nIn the winter night sky, look above Orion and you'll find the two stars shining together.";
"constellation.gemini.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.gemini.story.4.content" = "You, born between May 21 and June 21.\n\nGemini is a star that is never alone. Always two, always knowing how to share.\n\nJust as Pollux shared his immortality, you too carry that kind of heart. Wanting to share what is precious together.\n\nIf the two stars shine side by side tonight, it may be a sign that someone is beside you.";
"constellation.gemini.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.gemini.relation.1.name" = "Taurus";
"constellation.gemini.relation.1.desc" = "Neighbors in the winter sky";
"constellation.gemini.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.gemini.relation.2.name" = "Orion";
"constellation.gemini.relation.2.desc" = "Forms the winter triangle together";
"constellation.gemini.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.gemini.relation.3.name" = "Cancer";
"constellation.gemini.relation.3.desc" = "Bridges the way to the spring sky";
"constellation.gemini.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.gemini.relation.4.name" = "Sagittarius";
"constellation.gemini.relation.4.desc" = "Near the galactic center on the opposite side";

// MARK: - Cancer
"constellation.cancer.name" = "Cancer";
"constellation.cancer.description" = "Like the moon embracing the sea,\nyour star quietly shines\nbeside someone.";
"constellation.cancer.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.cancer.story.1.content" = "On the day Hercules fought the Lernaean Hydra, Hera sought to stop him.\n\nShe sent a crab from the sea to pinch Hercules on the foot. It was a small crab. Hercules crushed it underfoot, and so the crab died.\n\nHera, moved by that loyal crab, placed it in the sky. Though its mission had failed, it had held its ground to the very end.\n\nCancer knows that what matters is the heart, not the result.";
"constellation.cancer.story.2.title" = "Praesepe — The Beehive Cluster";
"constellation.cancer.story.2.content" = "At the center of Cancer lies a star cluster called Praesepe.\n\nTo the naked eye it looks like a faint cloud, but through a telescope it is a cluster of hundreds of stars. About 577 light-years away.\n\nIn ancient Greece, this dim glow was called 'the manger of the donkeys.' The two stars on either side of Cancer were the donkeys, and Praesepe was the manger.\n\nOn a clear night, find Cancer and look at its center to see that faint light. The light made together by hundreds of stars.";
"constellation.cancer.story.3.title" = "Gateway of the Summer Sky";
"constellation.cancer.story.3.content" = "Cancer lies along the ecliptic.\n\nIt sits at the crossroads where the sun, moon, and planets pass. Ancient astronomers called the moment the sun entered Cancer the summer solstice — the longest day of the year.\n\nPrecession has since moved the solstice point, but the English name for the Tropic of Cancer still carries the constellation's name.\n\nA small and dim constellation, yet an important marker in the sky. Quietly holding its place.";
"constellation.cancer.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.cancer.story.4.content" = "You, born between June 22 and July 22.\n\nCancer is a quiet star. Not flashy, but one that holds its place to the very end.\n\nJust as the small crab pinched Hercules, you too know the heart that does not give up. And that heart matters more than the result.\n\nTonight, look for Cancer shining quietly. Hundreds of stars are looking at you together.";
"constellation.cancer.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.cancer.relation.1.name" = "Gemini";
"constellation.cancer.relation.1.desc" = "Watches over the space between winter and spring";
"constellation.cancer.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.cancer.relation.2.name" = "Hydra";
"constellation.cancer.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through the myth of Hercules";
"constellation.cancer.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.cancer.relation.3.name" = "Leo";
"constellation.cancer.relation.3.desc" = "Companion in the spring sky";
"constellation.cancer.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.cancer.relation.4.name" = "Capricornus";
"constellation.cancer.relation.4.desc" = "Gazes at each other from opposite sides of the sky";

// MARK: - Leo
"constellation.leo.name" = "Leo";
"constellation.leo.description" = "Like the king of the night sky,\nyour star shines brightest\nwherever it goes.";
"constellation.leo.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.leo.story.1.content" = "The first labor of Hercules was to slay the Nemean Lion.\n\nNo ordinary weapon could wound it. Hercules finally strangled the lion with his bare hands. Then he used the lion's own claws to skin it and made it into armor.\n\nZeus placed that mighty lion in the sky. It had been an enemy, but its majesty was worthy of eternal remembrance.\n\nLeo is the king of the spring night sky. Regulus shines at its heart.";
"constellation.leo.story.2.title" = "King of the Spring Sky";
"constellation.leo.story.2.content" = "Leo rises high in the southern sky each spring.\n\nThe head looks like an inverted question mark — a shape called the Sickle. It looks like a lion roaring toward the heavens.\n\nThe Spring Triangle — formed by Denebola in Leo, Spica in Virgo, and Arcturus in Boötes — is a giant triangle in the spring sky.\n\nLook south on a spring night and you can find that proud lion.";
"constellation.leo.story.3.title" = "Regulus — The King's Star";
"constellation.leo.story.3.content" = "The heart of Leo, Regulus.\n\nMeaning 'little king' in Latin. About 79 light-years from Earth, about 360 times brighter than our sun.\n\nRevered as a royal star since antiquity. Babylon, Persia, and Rome all connected this star to kingship.\n\nRegulus lies on the ecliptic, so the moon frequently passes in front of it. Watching Regulus disappear behind the moon and reappear, you feel as though even stars breathe.";
"constellation.leo.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.leo.story.4.content" = "You, born between July 23 and August 22.\n\nLeo is a bold star. The first to catch the eye in the spring sky, with Regulus always shining at the center.\n\nThat boldness lives inside you. Not losing your own light even in a crowd.\n\nTonight, look for Regulus. The king's star will recognize you.";
"constellation.leo.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.leo.relation.1.name" = "Cancer";
"constellation.leo.relation.1.desc" = "Neighbors in the spring sky";
"constellation.leo.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.leo.relation.2.name" = "Hercules";
"constellation.leo.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through Hercules' first labor";
"constellation.leo.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.leo.relation.3.name" = "Virgo";
"constellation.leo.relation.3.desc" = "Forms the Spring Triangle together";
"constellation.leo.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.leo.relation.4.name" = "Aquarius";
"constellation.leo.relation.4.desc" = "Balances from the opposite side of the sky";

// MARK: - Virgo
"constellation.virgo.name" = "Virgo";
"constellation.virgo.description" = "With a delicate thread of light,\nyour star illuminates a small path\nthrough someone's darkness.";
"constellation.virgo.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.virgo.story.1.content" = "Virgo tells the story of Demeter, or perhaps Persephone.\n\nPersephone, daughter of Demeter the goddess of the earth, was playing in a field of flowers when Hades abducted her. Demeter wandered the whole world searching for her daughter, and while she did, the earth withered.\n\nIn the end, Persephone came to live six months underground and six months above. Each spring when Persephone returned to the earth, Demeter rejoiced and made the land flourish.\n\nVirgo shining in the spring sky is the trace of that joy.";
"constellation.virgo.story.2.title" = "Astraea's Scales";
"constellation.virgo.story.2.content" = "Virgo is also the goddess of justice, Astraea.\n\nAs the Golden Age ended and humans fell into corruption, the gods departed one by one for the sky. Astraea stayed on earth the longest, trying to uphold justice.\n\nWhen she finally ascended, she left her scales behind. Those scales became Libra, right beside Virgo.\n\nVirgo and Libra stand side by side. Justice and balance, together.";
"constellation.virgo.story.3.title" = "Spica — The Wheat Sheaf";
"constellation.virgo.story.3.content" = "The brightest star in Virgo, Spica.\n\nMeaning 'wheat sheaf' in Latin. The sheaf of wheat held in the maiden's hand became a star.\n\nSpica, about 250 light-years away, is actually a binary star — two stars orbiting each other. So close that their mutual gravity has stretched them into an oval shape.\n\nIf you see a bright blue star in the night sky, that is Spica.";
"constellation.virgo.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.virgo.story.4.content" = "You, born between August 23 and September 22.\n\nVirgo is a delicate star. One that tends the earth, creates seasons, and brings abundance.\n\nThat attentiveness lives inside you. Eyes that miss nothing small, a heart that quietly cares.\n\nOn a night when Spica glows blue, that light is crossing 250 light-years to reach you.";
"constellation.virgo.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.virgo.relation.1.name" = "Leo";
"constellation.virgo.relation.1.desc" = "Shines side by side in the spring sky";
"constellation.virgo.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.virgo.relation.2.name" = "Libra";
"constellation.virgo.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through Astraea's scales";
"constellation.virgo.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.virgo.relation.3.name" = "Libra";
"constellation.virgo.relation.3.desc" = "Companion bridging spring into summer";
"constellation.virgo.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.virgo.relation.4.name" = "Pisces";
"constellation.virgo.relation.4.desc" = "Faces each other from opposite sides of the sky";

// MARK: - Libra
"constellation.libra.name" = "Libra";
"constellation.libra.description" = "With a balanced light,\nyour star creates gentle ripples\non a quiet sea.";
"constellation.libra.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.libra.story.1.content" = "Libra is the scales of Astraea, goddess of justice.\n\nIn the Golden Age, gods lived among humans. But as humans fell into corruption, the gods departed one by one for the sky. Astraea stayed on earth the longest, trying to uphold justice.\n\nWhen she too finally ascended, she hung her scales in the sky. Hoping that one day justice would return to the world.\n\nLibra is the only inanimate object among the twelve signs of the zodiac.";
"constellation.libra.story.2.title" = "The Secret of the Scales";
"constellation.libra.story.2.content" = "The two bright stars of Libra carry special names.\n\nZubenelgenubi — 'the southern claw of the scorpion.' Zubeneschamali — 'the northern claw of the scorpion.'\n\nAs the names reveal, the stars of Libra were once considered part of Scorpius. They were later separated into a new constellation during ancient Rome, in honor of Julius Caesar.\n\nThe stars of the scales still carry the memory of the scorpion in their names. That trace remains even now.";
"constellation.libra.story.3.title" = "A Time of Balance";
"constellation.libra.story.3.content" = "Libra is also the guardian of the equinoxes.\n\nAt the autumnal equinox — when day and night are equal — the sun is near Libra. The moment balance is achieved.\n\nThe ancients saw the autumn equinox as the year's point of balance. The time to finish the harvest and prepare for winter. The time for the scales to find equilibrium.\n\nOn the night Libra rises, the sky too finds a moment of balance.";
"constellation.libra.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.libra.story.4.content" = "You, born between September 23 and October 23.\n\nLibra is a star that knows balance. A heart that tries not to lean one way, that seeks to see everything fairly.\n\nJust as Astraea stayed on earth to the very end, you too carry a sense of justice that does not give up.\n\nIf the scales are finding balance tonight, that is something happening inside you too.";
"constellation.libra.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.libra.relation.1.name" = "Virgo";
"constellation.libra.relation.1.desc" = "Watches over the space between spring and summer";
"constellation.libra.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.libra.relation.2.name" = "Virgo";
"constellation.libra.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through Astraea's scales";
"constellation.libra.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.libra.relation.3.name" = "Scorpius";
"constellation.libra.relation.3.desc" = "Companion in the summer sky";
"constellation.libra.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.libra.relation.4.name" = "Aries";
"constellation.libra.relation.4.desc" = "Balances from the opposite side of the sky";

// MARK: - Scorpius
"constellation.scorpio.name" = "Scorpius";
"constellation.scorpio.description" = "Even from the depths of the sea,\nyour starlight reaches\nwhere no one else knows.";
"constellation.scorpio.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.scorpio.story.1.content" = "Orion was the greatest hunter in the world. But his arrogance was his undoing.\n\nWhen he boasted he would hunt every beast in the world, Gaia, goddess of the earth, grew furious. She sent a scorpion, and the scorpion stung Orion on the heel.\n\nAnd so Orion fell. Zeus placed them both in the sky, but fearing they would fight again, he put them on opposite sides.\n\nNever to meet again.";
"constellation.scorpio.story.2.title" = "Master of the Summer Night";
"constellation.scorpio.story.2.content" = "Scorpius is the ruler of the summer night sky.\n\nIts S-shaped body stretches across the southern sky. In Korea it sits low near the horizon, so you need a clear, open view to see it well.\n\nNear the tail of Scorpius is where the Milky Way shines brightest. The direction of our galaxy's center.\n\nOn a summer night, look south and you can see the red Antares alongside the pouring Milky Way.";
"constellation.scorpio.story.3.title" = "Antares — The Red Heart";
"constellation.scorpio.story.3.content" = "The heart of Scorpius, Antares.\n\nMeaning 'rival of Mars.' Named because its red glow so closely resembles the planet Mars.\n\nAbout 550 light-years from Earth. A red supergiant 700 times the size of our sun. If Antares were placed where the sun is, it would swallow the orbit of Mars.\n\nOne day Antares will end its life in a supernova explosion. Even now, Antares is burning.";
"constellation.scorpio.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.scorpio.story.4.content" = "You, born between October 24 and November 22.\n\nScorpius is an intense star. One that burns red, feels deeply, and once it decides, goes all the way.\n\nJust as Antares burns, you too carry that passion inside. Quiet, but burning hot.\n\nTonight, find the red star glowing in the southern sky. That is your heart.";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.1.name" = "Libra";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.1.desc" = "Neighbors in the summer sky";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.2.type" = "Eternal enemy";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.2.name" = "Orion";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.2.desc" = "A star of fate that can never meet";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.3.name" = "Sagittarius";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.3.desc" = "Shines together near the Milky Way in the summer night sky";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.4.name" = "Taurus";
"constellation.scorpio.relation.4.desc" = "On the opposite side of the sky with Orion";

// MARK: - Sagittarius
"constellation.sagittarius.name" = "Sagittarius";
"constellation.sagittarius.description" = "Like a light that never stops moving,\nyour star travels new horizons\neven at this very moment.";
"constellation.sagittarius.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.sagittarius.story.1.content" = "Sagittarius is the centaur Chiron.\n\nAmong the centaurs — half human, half horse — Chiron was different. Unlike the wild and savage others, Chiron was wise and gentle. He was the great teacher of Achilles and Asclepius.\n\nOne day a poisoned arrow from Hercules accidentally struck Chiron. Being immortal, he could not die, and the pain went on and on.\n\nChiron chose to give his immortality to Prometheus and die in peace.";
"constellation.sagittarius.story.2.title" = "Heart of the Milky Way";
"constellation.sagittarius.story.2.content" = "The arrow of Sagittarius points toward Scorpius.\n\nAnd in that direction lies the center of our galaxy. That is why the Milky Way near Sagittarius appears brightest and widest on summer nights.\n\nThe teapot-shaped star cluster is the center of Sagittarius. The hazy light rising like steam from the teapot lid is the Milky Way.\n\nFind Sagittarius on a clear summer night and you can see the heart of our galaxy.";
"constellation.sagittarius.story.3.title" = "Kaus Australis — The Southern Bow";
"constellation.sagittarius.story.3.content" = "The brightest star in Sagittarius, Kaus Australis.\n\nMeaning 'the southern end of the bow' in Arabic. About 143 light-years from Earth, about 375 times brighter than our sun.\n\nAt the tip of the arrow drawn by Chiron's bow, the center of the galaxy lies in that direction.\n\nWhen Chiron drew his bow thousands of years ago, was he aiming at the heart of our galaxy?";
"constellation.sagittarius.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.sagittarius.story.4.content" = "You, born between November 23 and December 21.\n\nSagittarius is a free star. The arrow always points forward, dreaming beyond the horizon.\n\nJust as Chiron chose to teach, you too carry things inside you that you want to share.\n\nTonight, turn your eyes in the direction the arrow points. The center of the Milky Way is right there.";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.1.name" = "Scorpius";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.1.desc" = "Guards the Milky Way together in the summer night sky";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.2.name" = "Centaurus";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.2.desc" = "Connected as fellow centaurs";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.3.type" = "Milky Way companion";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.3.name" = "Aquila";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.3.desc" = "Shines together above the Milky Way";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.4.name" = "Gemini";
"constellation.sagittarius.relation.4.desc" = "Faces each other from opposite sides of the sky";

// MARK: - Capricornus
"constellation.capricorn.name" = "Capricornus";
"constellation.capricorn.description" = "A light that has endured long,\nyour star quietly waits\nfor someone's dawn.";
"constellation.capricorn.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.capricorn.story.1.content" = "It was the day Pan was fleeing from Typhon.\n\nThe gods by the Nile all transformed into animals and fled. Pan tried to become a fish, but in his panic only half transformed. The top half a goat, the bottom half a fish — a strange sight.\n\nZeus saw that ridiculous form and laughed, then placed him in the sky.\n\nAs a constellation to show that it is okay not to be perfect.";
"constellation.capricorn.story.2.title" = "A Quiet Star of the Winter Sky";
"constellation.capricorn.story.2.content" = "Capricornus is not one of the brighter constellations in the night sky.\n\nNo dazzling Orion, no red scorpion. But it was important since ancient times. The day the sun entered Capricornus was the winter solstice — the longest night of the year.\n\nPrecession has since moved the solstice point, but the English name for the Tropic of Capricorn still carries the constellation's name.\n\nQuiet, but holding its place.";
"constellation.capricorn.story.3.title" = "Deneb Algedi — The Goat's Tail";
"constellation.capricorn.story.3.content" = "The brightest star in Capricornus, Deneb Algedi.\n\nMeaning 'the tail of the goat' in Arabic. A relatively close star, about 39 light-years from Earth.\n\nDeneb Algedi is an eclipsing binary. Because two stars orbit each other while blocking one another, its brightness changes periodically. A star that dims and brightens slightly every 24 hours.\n\nIt looks like one from the outside, but it is actually two together. True to Capricornus — a star where outside and inside differ.";
"constellation.capricorn.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.capricorn.story.4.content" = "You, born between December 22 and January 19.\n\nCapricornus is a steady star. Like a goat climbing a high mountain, slow but never stopping.\n\nMoving forward even when not perfect. Like Pan who fled with only a half-transformation, the courage to begin even when not ready.\n\nThat is what your star teaches.";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.1.name" = "Sagittarius";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.1.desc" = "Watches over the space between summer and autumn";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.2.name" = "Aquarius";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through the stories of the Olympian gods";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.3.name" = "Aquarius";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.3.desc" = "Companion in the autumn night sky";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.4.name" = "Cancer";
"constellation.capricorn.relation.4.desc" = "Balances from the opposite side of the sky";

// MARK: - Aquarius
"constellation.aquarius.name" = "Aquarius";
"constellation.aquarius.description" = "Like water flowing freely,\nyour star shines without borders\nacross every corner of the world.";
"constellation.aquarius.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.aquarius.story.1.content" = "Aquarius tells the story of Ganymede.\n\nGanymede, prince of Troy, was the most beautiful boy in the world. Zeus transformed into an eagle and carried him to Olympus.\n\nGanymede was given the role of pouring nectar for the gods. Holding a golden water jar, serving the immortal gods forever.\n\nSome say he was happy. Ganymede, who became a star and pours water from the sky for eternity.";
"constellation.aquarius.story.2.title" = "The Eagle and the Boy";
"constellation.aquarius.story.2.content" = "The eagle that carried Ganymede is still in the sky today.\n\nAquila — the bright star Altair in the summer night sky is its eye. Still flying near Aquarius.\n\nBefore Ganymede ascended to Olympus, his father King Tros wept with grief. Zeus, feeling sorry, sent two golden grapevines and two immortal horses as gifts.\n\nStill, the father must have missed him. Looking up at his son pouring water from the sky.";
"constellation.aquarius.story.3.title" = "Sadalsuud — The Luckiest Star";
"constellation.aquarius.story.3.content" = "The brightest star in Aquarius, Sadalsuud.\n\nMeaning 'luckiest of the lucky' in Arabic. Named because it rose above the horizon heralding the start of spring. The star that brings the spring rains.\n\nA supergiant about 610 light-years from Earth. A star 2,200 times brighter than our sun.\n\nA star that announces spring, brings rain, and pours fortune. Just as Ganymede pours water.";
"constellation.aquarius.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.aquarius.story.4.content" = "You, born between January 20 and February 18.\n\nAquarius is a star of giving. Pouring water, letting it flow, emptying rather than filling.\n\nYou too carry that kind of heart. Wanting to share what you have, hoping the world becomes a little better.\n\nTonight Ganymede is pouring water from the sky. Hoping that water reaches you.";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.1.name" = "Capricornus";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.1.desc" = "Neighbors in the autumn sky";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.2.name" = "Aquila";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through the eagle that carried Ganymede";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.3.name" = "Pisces";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.3.desc" = "Adorns the autumn night sky together";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.4.name" = "Leo";
"constellation.aquarius.relation.4.desc" = "Faces each other from opposite sides of the sky";

// MARK: - Pisces
"constellation.pisces.name" = "Pisces";
"constellation.pisces.description" = "Between dream and reality,\nyour star reflects on a quiet sea\nwarming someone's night.";
"constellation.pisces.story.1.title" = "Birth";
"constellation.pisces.story.1.content" = "On the day Typhon attacked Olympus, Aphrodite and Eros were by the Euphrates River.\n\nThe two transformed into fish and leaped into the river, tying themselves together with a cord so they would not lose each other.\n\nThat cord can still be seen in Pisces today. Two fish facing opposite directions, connected by a cord in the middle.\n\nAphrodite engraved that moment in the sky. To remember the heart that would not let go.";
"constellation.pisces.story.2.title" = "The Gate of Spring";
"constellation.pisces.story.2.content" = "Pisces is the last constellation of the zodiac.\n\nIf Aries is the beginning, Pisces is the end and the gate of beginning again. When the sun passes through Pisces, it enters Aries where spring begins.\n\nThe vernal equinox — the point where spring starts — now lies within Pisces. It moved there through precession.\n\nWhere end and beginning meet. Pisces guards that threshold.";
"constellation.pisces.story.3.title" = "The Secret of Two Fish";
"constellation.pisces.story.3.content" = "The two fish of Pisces look in different directions.\n\nOne faces north, one faces west. Looking in opposite directions but connected by a cord.\n\nAstronomically, Pisces is a very faint constellation. Hard to spot. But within it lies the vernal equinox, and the ecliptic passes through it.\n\nThere are things that matter even when they cannot be seen. Like Pisces.";
"constellation.pisces.story.4.title" = "Your Star";
"constellation.pisces.story.4.content" = "You, born between February 19 and March 20.\n\nPisces is a star of connection. A cord that does not break even while looking in opposite directions.\n\nYou too carry that kind of bond inside. People who remain connected even when far apart, things you do not want to let go.\n\nTonight two fish are swimming through the sky. Holding the cord that binds them to each other.";
"constellation.pisces.relation.1.type" = "Nearest in the sky";
"constellation.pisces.relation.1.name" = "Aquarius";
"constellation.pisces.relation.1.desc" = "Shines side by side in the autumn sky";
"constellation.pisces.relation.2.type" = "Mythological link";
"constellation.pisces.relation.2.name" = "Aquarius";
"constellation.pisces.relation.2.desc" = "Connected through the story of Aphrodite and Eros";
"constellation.pisces.relation.3.type" = "Seasonal companion";
"constellation.pisces.relation.3.name" = "Aries";
"constellation.pisces.relation.3.desc" = "Winter night sky companion leading into spring";
"constellation.pisces.relation.4.type" = "Opposite constellation";
"constellation.pisces.relation.4.name" = "Virgo";
"constellation.pisces.relation.4.desc" = "Balances from the opposite side of the sky";

